Turkish Banks Give Offers on Loans During Ramadan, Dunya Says

-- B y   B e n j a m i n   H a r v e y
-- 
2011-08-11T06:05:22Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-11/turkish-banks-give-offers-on-loans-during-ramadan-dunya-says.html
Turkish banks are offering customers
incentives such as longer maturities, larger amounts and delayed
payments for loans during the Muslim holy month of Ramadan,
 Dunya  newspaper reported.  Akbank TAS (AKBNK)  is giving loans of as much as 20,000 liras
($11,300) with payment terms of up to 60 months and a grace
period of three months, the newspaper said.  Turkiye Garanti
Bankasi AS (GARAN)  offers special packages for the holiday ranging from
5,000 to 50,000 liras, it said.  Turkiye Ekonomi Bankasi AS is promoting a Ramadan package
that has a grace period of no payments until after the next
major Muslim holiday, the Feast of the Sacrifice, which ends
Nov. 10, the newspaper said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Benjamin Harvey in Istanbul at 
 bharvey11@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Gavin Serkin at 
 gserkin@bloomberg.net  